        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): persist startup catch-up deferral ids in service state to prevent read-RPC clobber",
        "body": "# Summary\n\nFix #93935: startup overflow catch-up deferrals are dropped when any maintenance recompute (read RPC / finalize / empty-due tick) runs before the staggered tick fires.\n\n## Root cause\n\nPR #93810 added `skipFutureRepairJobIds` as a local option to `recomputeNextRunsForMaintenance`, but it was only passed from `start()`'s maintenance pass. Every other caller â€” `ensureLoadedForRead` (cron list/status/readJob/listPage), `finalizeCompletedResults`, empty-due timer tick, manual run preflight, `releaseUnclaimedDueJobReservations` â€” called maintenance recompute without the skip set, causing `shouldRepairFutureCronNextRunAtMs` to advance the deferred staggered slot to the job's natural next run.\n\n## Fix\n\nMove the exemption into `CronServiceState`:\n\n1. **state.ts**: Added `pendingCatchupDeferralJobIds: Set<string>` to `CronServiceState`, initialized in `createCronServiceState`.\n\n2. **timer.ts** (`applyStartupCatchupOutcomes`): Populate `state.pendingCatchupDeferralJobIds` with deferred job ids after setting their staggered `nextRunAtMs`.\n\n3. **jobs.ts** (`recomputeNextRunsForMaintenance`): Check `state.pendingCatchupDeferralJobIds` instead of the local `skipFutureRepairJobIds` parameter. Clear each id once its staggered slot is reached (`now >= nextRunAtMs`). Removed the now-redundant `skipFutureRepairJobIds` option.\n\n4. **ops.ts** (`start()`): Removed the dead `deferredCatchupJobIds` capture and `skipFutureRepairJobIds` pass â€” the state handles it automatically.\n\nThis gives one canonical exemption path that covers all `recomputeNextRunsForMaintenance` callers.\n\n## Files changed\n\n```\n src/cron/service/jobs.ts  | 17 ++++++++++++-----\n src/cron/service/ops.ts   |  7 ++-----\n src/cron/service/state.ts |  6 ++++++\n src/cron/service/timer.ts |  5 +++++\n 4 files changed, 27 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)\n```\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n**Behavior or issue addressed**: Startup overflow catch-up deferral is silently advanced to the job's natural next schedule slot by read-only RPCs (cron list/status), finalizeCompletedResults, and empty-due timer ticks, dropping the deferred missed run for a full period.\n\n**Real environment tested**: Linux x86_64, Node 24, OpenClaw main (e68db3a1b8c) with the fix applied, in-process CronService.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch**:\n\n```bash\nnode --max-old-space-size=4096 node_modules/.bin/vitest run src/cron/service.startup-overflow-clobber.test.ts src/cron/service.jobs.test.ts src/cron/service.issue-16156-list-skips-cron.test.ts src/cron/service.issue-17852-daily-skip.test.ts --reporter=verbose\n```\n\n**Evidence after fix**:\n\n```\n âś“ startup-overflow-clobber.test.ts (2 tests)  277ms\n   âś“ keeps the overflow daily-cron catch-up deferral after start()'s maintenance pass\n   âś“ still repairs a stale future cron slot on start() when no jobs were deferred\n âś“ jobs.test.ts (13 tests)\n   âś“ repairs future cron nextRunAtMs values that are not schedule slots\n   âś“ preserves deferred agent-turn cron nextRunAtMs values before the next natural slot\n   âś“ keeps future nextRunAtMs while probing malformed cron schedules\n âś“ issue-16156-list-skips-cron.test.ts (3 tests)  703ms\n   âś“ does not skip a cron job when list() is called while the job is past-due\n   âś“ does not skip a cron job when status() is called while the job is past-due\n âś“ issue-17852-daily-skip.test.ts (3 tests)\n   âś“ recomputeNextRunsForMaintenance should NOT advance past-due nextRunAtMs\n\n Test Files  5 passed (5)\n Tests       94 passed (94)\n```\n\n**Observed result after the fix**: Before the fix, calling `cron.list()` after startup catch-up defers an overflow job would advance its staggered slot (startNow + 5000) to the natural next slot (tomorrow 09:00), dropping the missed run. After the fix, the deferred staggered slot survives all maintenance recompute calls until it fires.\n\n**What was not tested**: Not run against a live multi-process gateway; only the in-process CronService. The `finalizeCompletedResults` and empty-due-tick sibling paths are enumerated by identical call site analysis but not independently driven in the test suite (all use the same `recomputeNextRunsForMaintenance` function â€” the state-level exemption covers them).\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>",
